A film by @type7

Son of legendary Australian shaper and surfer Neal Purchase, Neal Purchase Jnr was more or less born into the profession and culture. Growing up competing, Neal found his way as a free surfer, later following his father’s footsteps as a shaper. Now, Neal is renowned internationally for his surfing ability as well as his craftsmanship.

His iconic Duo, Quartet and Single fin shapes are a modern day homage to the past, something he credits to his father’s influence. An ever evolving refinement of classic designs, Neal’s boards are just as much a work of art as they are high performance surf craft. 

Yet despite his status in the surf world, 'Purcho' is one of the most kind, humble people you will meet. In fact, he scored the soundtrack for this very film 🏄‍♂️

Directed by @caplice
Starring @nealpurchasejnr
Production Company @mojaveproductions

node.text:
This is the hill of San Michele in the historic Swiss town of Bellinzona. Records suggest there have been fortifications here for at least fourteen hundred years, while the striking San Gimignano-esque towers have been here since the Milanese occupation of the renaissance. Though great expense may once have been spent on the castle’s impenetrable walls, a comparable effort has been made in modern times to let you walk right under them.

The dramatic concrete entrance that pries apart the cliff face is as impressive as any of the more ancient parts of the site. The twenty foot doorway stops you dead in your tracks, as though it thresholds a pharaoh’s tomb and you ought to enter with your eyes open. At the end of the corridor, the hemispherical atrium offers you a moment’s rest before you climb the spiral stairs that bore through to the hilltop. It’s the perfect example of how you make the most of a simple design task.

Photos by @simonebossiphotographer 
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

Son of legendary Australian shaper and surfer Neal Purchase, Neal Purchase Jnr was more or less born into the profession and culture. Growing up competing, Neal found his way as a free surfer, later following his father’s footsteps as a shaper. Now, Neal is renowned internationally for his surfing ability as well as his craftsmanship.

His iconic Duo, Quartet and Single fin shapes are a modern day homage to the past, something he credits to his father’s influence. An ever evolving refinement of classic designs, Neal’s boards are just as much a work of art as they are high performance surf craft. 

Yet despite his status in the surf world, 'Purcho' is one of the most kind, humble people you will meet. In fact, he scored the soundtrack for this very film 🏄‍♂️

If there’s one thing to take away from our visit to the Barcelona outpost of the boutique film processing gurus at @carmencitafilmlab_jp , it’s that film is very much alive and here to stay. “We can’t imagine how the world would be without the ability to capture light and render it as an image,” explains Abel, one of the small team of film processing mavens who make up the team behind Carmencita, all film die-hards; “I am the son of a photographer, and I’ve always lived in an analog world when it comes to photography.”

Since 2012 this group, founded in Valencia, have been scanning and processing, using their expertise of what was for many years a dying trade. Before its renaissance, many of the film stocks we know and love disappeared from store shelves entirely. If you happened to be in a city, perhaps you had a contact with a fridge full of now exotic, but once common rolls film stocks. Now, thankfully, film lives on in a shaky marriage with digital. “We don’t actually think it’s better or worse,” Abel says. “They are ultimately different processes in which the light affects in different ways, and in the case of analog, there are actually more people in the chain and interpretation of the work.” 

“The beauty of film is that every part of the process influences the result and everything starts with developing, so we couldn’t take it more seriously,” Abel continues. Nearly 300,000 rolls have passed through their process, from as far as Japan. With that kind of responsibility the team approach their craft with an obsessive attention to detail, down to the scanners they use; “The Noritsu [HS-1800 film scanner, for any die-hards out there] really has it’s own flavour” Abel explains of their different scanners, which are the final step before a film photograph is truly digitised and returns to the original photographer, converted from pure chemistry into binary code. “Either you develop it right or you develop it wrong.”
